comments.body:
`prop:step2` claims $P^{(2)}_j(\rho,\nu)=c^\rho_\nu/D$ with $D=\prod_{k<j}(x_k-t^{-n+2})\prod_{k>j}(x_k-t^{-n+1})$, equivalently $P_jP^{(2)}_j=c^\rho_\nu/e^*_{n-1}$. The proof is labelled '[Idea]' and merely asserts that dividing each ball/pairing weight of the unique $\overline Q\in\mathcal G^\rho_\nu$ by the matching factor of $D$ 'reproduces, case by case, the skip/settle probabilities $1-p_k,1-q_k,p_k,q_k$.'

The actual case analysis is absent. One must verify:
- each of the four ball/pairing weights ($x_k-t^{-(n-1)}$, $x_k$, $t^{-(n-1)}$, and the pairing weight $(1-t)t^{\mathrm{skip}}$) divided by the corresponding factor of $D$ equals the correct $p_k$, $q_k$, $1-p_k$, or $1-q_k$;
- a full clockwise sweep telescopes to a single transition probability;
- the claim that columns $k>j$ 'never move, factor 1' is consistent with $\rho_j=0$ and the sweep direction.

Until this is written out, $P^{(2)}_j$ is not established to be a probability nor equal to $c^\rho_\nu/D$.
